solution.p:
The lines are parallel if their slopes are equal. We can find the slope of the first line by putting its equation into slope-intercept form. We solve for y:
\begin{aligned}[t] 3x+6y \amp = 6 \amp \amp \blert{\text{Subtract}~ 3x~ \text{from both sides.}}\\ 6y \amp = -3x + 6 \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by}~6.}\\ y \amp = \dfrac{-3x}{6} + \dfrac{6}{6} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Simplify.}}\\ y = \amp = -\dfrac{1}{2}x + 1\\ \end{aligned}
The slope of the first line is m_1=-\dfrac{1}{2}. The equation of the second line is already in slope-intercept form, and its slope is m_2=-\dfrac{1}{2}. Thus, m_1=m_2, so the lines are parallel.

subsection.p:
The lines appear to be perpendicular.  The relationship between the slopes of perpendicular lines is not as easy to see as the relationship for parallel lines.  However, for this example, m_1=\dfrac{2}{3} and m_2=-\dfrac{3}{2}.  Note that
m_2=-\dfrac{3}{2} = \dfrac{-1}{\dfrac{2}{3}} = \dfrac{-1}{m_1}

This relationship holds for any two perpendicular lines with slopes m_1 and m_2, as long as m_1 \not= 0 and m_2 \not= 0.
